---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import { getCollection } from 'astro:content';
import { siteConfig } from '../site.config';

const posts = (await getCollection('blog')).sort(
  (a, b) => b.data.date.getTime() - a.data.date.getTime()
);
const latestPosts = posts.slice(0, 2);

const personJsonLd = {
  '@context': 'https://schema.org',
  '@type': 'Person',
  name: siteConfig.fullName,
  url: siteConfig.domain,
  sameAs: [siteConfig.socialLinks.linkedin, siteConfig.socialLinks.github],
  jobTitle: siteConfig.tagline,
  description: siteConfig.tagline
};
---

<BaseLayout
  title="RUPAN PRASAI | Engineer, Builder, and Problem Solver"
  description="Official website of RUPAN PRASAI. Explore projects, technical writing, and practical engineering insights focused on reliable software systems."
  canonicalPath="/"
>
  <h1>RUPAN PRASAI</h1>
  <p class="meta">{siteConfig.tagline} · {siteConfig.location}</p>

  <p>
    I build software with a practical mindset: solve the real problem first, then design systems that remain easy to operate as usage grows.
    Over the years, I have learned that successful engineering is usually less about flashy frameworks and more about reliable foundations,
    clear communication, and disciplined execution. That perspective shapes how I approach every project, whether I am prototyping a new
    feature, shipping a production release, or tightening an existing workflow that has become fragile under change.
  </p>
  <p>
    My work typically sits at the intersection of backend architecture, developer tooling, and product delivery. I enjoy translating ambiguous
    requirements into a roadmap that teams can trust, then building toward measurable outcomes with steady iteration. In practice, that means
    writing maintainable code, creating predictable deployment pipelines, and setting quality checks that catch problems early. I care deeply
    about reducing operational surprises, because reliability is not only a technical metric—it is a user experience promise.
  </p>
  <p>
    Beyond implementation, I pay close attention to how decisions age. Good architecture is not just about what works today; it is about what
    your team can understand and improve six months from now. I prioritize readable systems, useful observability, and documentation that keeps
    pace with reality. I also value thoughtful trade-offs: sometimes the right solution is sophisticated, and sometimes it is intentionally simple
    so the team can move faster with confidence. Knowing the difference is a skill I continue to refine with each build.
  </p>
  <p>
    This website is a living snapshot of how I think and what I ship. You will find selected projects, technical writing, and ways to connect.
    If you are working on something that needs careful engineering and dependable execution, I am always open to meaningful conversations.
  </p>

  <section aria-labelledby="featured-projects">
    <h2 id="featured-projects">Featured Projects</h2>
    <div class="card-grid">
      {siteConfig.projects.map((project) => (
        <article class="card">
          <h3><a href={project.url}>{project.name}</a></h3>
          <p>{project.description}</p>
          <p class="meta">{project.techStack.join(' · ')}</p>
        </article>
      ))}
    </div>
    <p><a href="/projects">See all project details on the Projects page.</a></p>
  </section>

  <section aria-labelledby="latest-writing">
    <h2 id="latest-writing">Latest Writing</h2>
    <div class="card-grid">
      {latestPosts.map((post) => (
        <article class="card">
          <h3><a href={`/blog/${post.slug}`}>{post.data.title}</a></h3>
          <p class="meta">
            <time datetime={post.data.date.toISOString()}>{post.data.date.toLocaleDateString('en-US', { year: 'numeric', month: 'long', day: 'numeric' })}</time>
          </p>
          <p>{post.data.description}</p>
        </article>
      ))}
    </div>
    <p><a href="/blog">Browse all posts.</a></p>
  </section>

  <script type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify(personJsonLd)} />
</BaseLayout>
